      <div class="text-xs text-slate leading-relaxed flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">1. SIP Future Value Compounding</h4>
        <p>
          A Systematic Investment Plan (SIP) allows recurring contributions. By default, standard financial plans compound returns monthly since contributions are monthly.
          Our standard engine calculates future value at the start of each month (annuity due) using:
        </p>
        <div class="p-2.5 bg-surface font-mono rounded-lg border border-hairline text-center text-primary">
          FV = P &times; [ (1 + i)<sup>n</sup> - 1 ] &times; (1 + i) / i
        </div>
        <p>
          Where <strong>P</strong> is the monthly investment, <strong>i</strong> is the monthly interest rate (r / 12 / 100), and <strong>n</strong> is the number of months.
        </p>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">2. Annual Step-up Calculations</h4>
        <p>
          A step-up SIP increases your monthly contribution annually. This reflects real-world career promotions and wage increments.
          Since the monthly investment changes every 12 months, our engine uses a monthly step-simulation loop:
        </p>
        <p class="italic">
          For each month: the contribution increases by the step-up percent at each 12-month interval boundary, and standard compounding returns apply:
          <code>balance = (balance + monthlyContribution) * (1 + monthlyRate)</code>.
        </p>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">3. Compounding Frequency Alternatives</h4>
        <p>
          You can toggle the compounding frequency. Standard mutual funds assume monthly, but selecting Yearly Compounding converts the rate to a yearly compounding equivalent before applying monthly contributions.
        </p>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">4. Estimates and Market Risk Disclaimer</h4>
        <p class="text-stone">
          Calculations are mathematical estimates assuming constant returns. Real mutual fund or equity returns are subject to volatility, inflation, and market risks.
        </p>
